In running a linear mixed-effects regression model, the familiarity of the sociopolitical issue was the strongest positive predictor of moral convictions `r statpresent(Familiar1_scaled,CorrelationLMERTest)` when either topic was selected as shown in @fig-alt-effectplot. On the other hand , the support variable was `r if(summary(CorrelationLMERTest)$coefficients[2,5]<0.05) "significant" else "not significant"` in predicting moral convictions`r statpresent(Support_left_scaled,CorrelationLMERTest)`.This suggests that the repeated exposure to an issue shapes the intensity of the moral beliefs more so than the political support for this issue.Through a Pearson correlation test, moral conviction and topic familiarity were also `r if(corr_estimate>0 & corr_pvalue<0.05) "positively correlated" else if (corr_estimate<0 & corr_pvalue<0.05) "negatively correlated" else "not correlated"` (`r round(corr_estimate,3)`, p `r if(corr_pvalue<0.001) "<0.001" else "=round(corr_pvalue,3)"`), where most of the highly familiar sociopolitical issues were highly moralized , as @fig-tileplot illustrates. Other demographic factors , including religiosity, did not significantly predict moral conviction scores.



